{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01HcVkdT3T8PXzcB5WLRzwk9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior for the spreadsheet formula engine and determine the minimum test level needed.\n\n1. **SUM(A1:A10) evaluates correctly**\n   - This is pure formula evaluation logic - parsing a range, summing values\n   - No I/O, no LLM, no OS\n   - MOCK-MISS: Single module (evaluator) logic\n   - Unit level - testing the evaluator function with known inputs\n\n2. **Cascaded formula evaluation (B1+1 where B1=A1*2)**\n   - Tests dependency resolution between cells\n   - Could be a single module if the evaluator handles this internally\n   - Actually this is about how the engine wires cells together - multiple cells interacting\n   - The failure only appears when cells reference each other, which is a module boundary between cell storage and evaluator\n   - Integration level - several modules wired together (cell store + evaluator + dependency resolver)\n\n3. **Circular dependency detection**\n   - This is algorithm/graph traversal logic\n   - Could be tested as a unit if the cycle detection is a self-contained algorithm\n   - The dependency graph traversal is internal logic\n   - Unit - cycle detection algorithm with a mock cell graph\n\n4. **VLOOKUP exact match**\n   - Pure function logic - lookup in a table\n   - No external dependencies\n   - Unit level\n\n5. **Nested IF conditions**\n   - Pure expression parsing and evaluation\n   - Unit level\n\n6. **CONCATENATE with empty cell handling**\n   - Pure function logic\n   - Unit level - testing the CONCATENATE function implementation\n\n7. **Cross-sheet reference resolution**\n   - References a cell in a different sheet\n   - This requires multiple sheets to be wired together\n   - Integration - sheet registry + evaluator working together\n\n8. **Recalculation in topological order when cell changes**\n   - This requires the dependency tracking and recalculation system to work together\n   - Multiple modules: dependency graph, topological sort, evaluator\n   - Integration level\n\n9. **Undo operation restores formula and computed values**\n   - Undo/redo requires the state management system\n   - Multiple modules: undo stack, cell store, evaluator\n   - Integration level\n\n10. **Save/load workbook with no data loss**\n    - Persistence layer needs to serialize and deserialize the entire workbook state\n    - Integration level - the core concern is whether the serialization format preserves all data correctly, which I can test with in-memory byte streams rather than actual filesystem operations\n\nLet me reconsider each more carefully:\n\n**Behavior 1: SUM(A1:A10)**\n- Single function evaluation\n- Unit: parse range, evaluate\n\n**Behavior 2: Cascaded formula (B1+1 where B1=A1*2)**\n- Multiple cells with formulas referencing each other\n- The failure mode surfaces at the boundary between cell storage and formula evaluation\n- Level: Integration\n\n**Behavior 3: Circular dependency detection**\n- The cycle detection algorithm itself is straightforward, but detecting it during actual evaluation requires the full cell resolution path to work\n- Level: Unit\n\n**Behavior 4: VLOOKUP exact match**\n- Pure function behavior with edge cases\n- Level: Unit\n\n**Behavior 5: Nested IF**\n- Expression parsing and evaluation\n- Level: Unit\n\n**Behavior 6: CONCATENATE with empty cells**\n- Function behavior with edge case handling\n- Level: Unit\n\n**Behavior 7: Cross-sheet reference**\n- Requires the sheet registry and evaluator to coordinate, with failures likely at that module boundary\n- Level: Integration\n\n**Behavior 8: Topological recalculation**\n- Dependency graph tracking and ensuring cells recalculate in the correct order across multiple modules\n\n, with failures appearing where those modules connect\n- Level: Integration\n\n**Behavior 9: Undo restores formula and computed values**\n- The undo stack, cell store, and evaluator all need to coordinate, particularly when triggering re-evaluation of dependent cells, with failures at the boundaries between undo state and cell/formula state\n- Level: Integration\n\n**Behavior 10: Save/load workbook**\n- The serialization logic itself determines whether data loss or precision changes occur, regardless of whether we use real filesystem I/O or an in-memory buffer\n- Level: Integration\n\nNow I'm working through the probability distributions for each behavior. Starting with SUM evaluation as a unit-level concern, then cascaded formulas and circular dependencies as integration-level issues. Finishing the cross-sheet reference entry, then moving through topological recalculation, undo operations, and save/load workbook behaviors. For the save/load case, I'm reconsidering whether the filesystem aspect—actual disk persistence rather than just in-memory serialization—should shift the weights, though Integration still seems like the primary failure mode.\n\nNow I'm revisiting behavior 3 on circular dependencies. The question is whether testing just the cycle detection algorithm in isolation counts as Unit, or if the full integration of formula evaluation feeding into dependency tracking warrants Integration. The phrasing \"the engine detects\" suggests the complete flow matters here.\n\nActually, a Unit test with a manually constructed dependency graph would be sufficient to catch both failure modes—whether the evaluator skips cycle checking entirely or the detection logic itself is flawed. I'll classify this as Unit.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13602,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13602},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0557ed17-6cc9-41b1-a6c7-ed70293a37d4"